## Where Prediction Markets Still Struggle

Honesty about limitations strengthens rather than weakens the case for prediction market utility. Polymarket accuracy demonstrably suffers in certain contexts. Black swan events—low-probability outcomes with massive consequences—remain systematically underpriced because traders have limited incentive to tie up capital in positions that almost never pay off. Markets on subjective outcomes, where resolution criteria involve judgment calls, attract manipulation and create resolution disputes that damage price signal quality. Political markets, while generally outperforming polls, can exhibit partisan bias when trader populations skew ideologically. Geographic clustering of participants can create blind spots on local information. And perhaps most importantly, markets cannot price what they cannot imagine—truly novel scenarios fall outside the forecasting framework entirely. Understanding these limitations helps traders calibrate their own confidence in market signals and identify opportunities where their edge might exceed the crowd's.

## Practical Implications for Using Market Signals

So how should you actually use Polymarket accuracy as an input for decision-making? Treat prices as the best available estimate given current information, not as certainties. Markets priced at 85% still resolve NO roughly 15% of the time—that's not a failure but the system working correctly. Compare market prices to your own analysis; persistent divergence either means you have superior information or you're missing something the market sees. High-volume markets on clear, binary outcomes with short time horizons deserve more confidence than thin, long-dated markets on ambiguous questions. Track which traders consistently outperform and weight their positions accordingly. Tools like [polymarket.tips](https://polymarket.tips) exist precisely to help identify when experienced traders are aligning on positions the broader market hasn't yet fully incorporated. [Browse the live markets on Polymarket](https://polymarket.com/?r=POLYTips) with the understanding that prices represent probabilities, not predictions—a crucial distinction that separates sophisticated market participants from those destined to learn expensive lessons about the difference between likely and certain.

